# Neuro-Salesman — Architecture Guide

This file describes the target architecture of Neuro-Salesman.

It is the source of truth for how the system should be structured as it evolves into a production-ready AI administrator.

Cursor must use this architecture when planning refactoring or implementing new features.

---

# 1. High-level architecture

Neuro-Salesman is an AI administrator system for expert businesses.

It supports:
- Telegram as conversational interface
- Web admin panel
- Web booking page
- CRM-like lead and conversation tracking
- FAQ and templates
- booking and reminders
- optional LLM fallback

Target architecture:

```text
Telegram / Web
      ↓
Conversation Engine
      ↓
Intent Layer
      ↓
Services / Tools
   - booking
   - faq
   - crm
   - reminders
   - handoff
      ↓
LLM fallback
      ↓
Database

This means:
	•	interfaces do not contain business logic
	•	dialog state is centralized
	•	user intent detection is centralized
	•	business actions are executed by services
	•	LLM is a fallback, not the primary source of truth

⸻

2. Design principles

2.1 Separation of responsibilities

Each layer must have one primary responsibility.

2.2 Production stability first

Booking flow and deployment stability are more important than fancy AI behavior.

2.3 Incremental refactoring

The project must be migrated step by step.
Never rewrite the whole system in one pass.

2.4 Shared logic across channels

Telegram and Web must use the same booking and FAQ logic.

2.5 AI as fallback

Business logic and templates come first.
LLM comes after structured logic.

⸻

3. Current and target system model

3.1 Current project reality

The project likely still contains:
	•	Telegram handlers with embedded business logic
	•	state logic distributed across handlers
	•	intent detection mixed with transport logic
	•	duplicated booking decisions
	•	partial refactoring toward better structure

3.2 Target project state

The project must move toward:
	•	centralized conversation engine
	•	centralized intent layer
	•	business services
	•	reusable integrations
	•	production-safe frontend
	•	stable timezone handling
	•	explicit CRM memory

⸻

4. Main layers

4.1 Interface layer

Interface layer includes:
	•	Telegram bot
	•	Web admin
	•	Web booking page
	•	API routes

Responsibilities:
	•	receive input
	•	render output
	•	call engine/services
	•	never own business logic

Examples:
	•	Telegram callback handlers
	•	FastAPI routes
	•	React pages and forms

Forbidden:
	•	heavy business decisions inside handlers
	•	direct state manipulation from many places
	•	duplicate booking logic in Telegram and Web separately

⸻

4.2 Conversation Engine

Conversation Engine is the heart of dialog orchestration.

Responsibilities:
	•	read conversation state
	•	update conversation state safely
	•	preserve consent and context
	•	determine current flow and step
	•	decide the next transition
	•	handle reset and recovery
	•	avoid stuck or looping flows

State must include fields like:
	•	flow
	•	step
	•	pd_consent
	•	goal
	•	format
	•	time_pref
	•	slot_id
	•	active_booking_id
	•	handoff_mode (or linked conversation flag)
	•	other context needed for progression

Rules:
	•	state updates must merge with previous state
	•	no direct full overwrite unless explicit reset
	•	consent must survive normal flow transitions
	•	successful completion must reset flow state cleanly
	•	broken flow must be recoverable through global intents

Target location:
	•	backend/app/conversation/

Suggested modules:
	•	engine.py
	•	state.py
	•	guards.py
	•	transitions.py
	•	context.py

⸻

4.3 Intent Layer

Intent Layer interprets what the user wants.

Responsibilities:
	•	detect user intent
	•	support global interrupts
	•	combine keyword/rule matching with current context
	•	optionally delegate unknown cases to LLM fallback

Supported intents should include:
	•	start
	•	help
	•	reset
	•	booking
	•	price
	•	faq
	•	handoff
	•	reschedule
	•	cancel
	•	free_question

Priority order:
	1.	explicit commands
	2.	global intents
	3.	current flow context
	4.	keyword/rule matching
	5.	LLM fallback if enabled

Rules:
	•	intent detection must be shared by Telegram and Web
	•	global intents must work from any flow
	•	intent output must be explicit and typed
	•	no duplicated keyword logic spread across handlers

Target location:
	•	backend/app/intents/

Suggested modules:
	•	detector.py
	•	rules.py
	•	keywords.py
	•	types.py

⸻

4.4 Services / Tools layer

Services perform business actions.

Required services:
	•	booking_service
	•	faq_service
	•	crm_service
	•	reminder_service
	•	handoff_service
	•	consent_service
	•	analytics_service
	•	settings_service

Responsibilities:
	•	implement business rules
	•	interact with repositories/models
	•	execute booking workflows
	•	manage reminders
	•	fetch FAQ answers
	•	update CRM state/history
	•	enforce business constraints

Rules:
	•	services should not own dialog orchestration
	•	services should not parse raw Telegram payloads
	•	services should be callable from different channels

Target location:
	•	backend/app/services/

Examples:
	•	booking_service creates booking transactionally
	•	reminder_service schedules or recreates reminders
	•	faq_service resolves template/KB answer
	•	crm_service updates client record/history
	•	consent_service records and checks PD consent

⸻

4.5 CRM layer

CRM is not a separate app. It is a data responsibility inside the backend.

Responsibilities:
	•	maintain client identity
	•	maintain conversation history
	•	maintain booking history
	•	maintain lead status
	•	maintain consent status
	•	support admin panel workflows

Important entities:
	•	Lead
	•	Conversation
	•	Message
	•	Booking
	•	Reminder
	•	Offer
	•	Knowledge Article
	•	Reply Template
	•	Expert Settings
	•	Schedule and exceptions

CRM must allow:
	•	tracking active and past clients
	•	inspecting lead source and history
	•	seeing current active booking
	•	switching to handoff mode
	•	reviewing no-show/cancel/lost status

⸻

4.6 LLM layer

LLM must be optional and bounded.

Responsibilities:
	•	help answer free-form questions
	•	rephrase answer more naturally
	•	assist conversational tone
	•	handle ambiguity when structured logic cannot answer

LLM must never be primary truth for:
	•	prices
	•	services
	•	availability
	•	contraindications
	•	business rules
	•	diagnosis

Execution order:
	1.	rules engine
	2.	templates
	3.	KB / FAQ mapping
	4.	LLM fallback

Required runtime controls:
	•	LLM_ENABLED
	•	timeout handling
	•	graceful failure
	•	logging

Target location:
	•	backend/app/integrations/llm/

Suggested modules:
	•	client.py
	•	prompts.py
	•	fallback.py
	•	guardrails.py
	•	formatter.py

⸻

5. Transport-specific integration

5.1 Telegram integration

Telegram is a transport channel.

Responsibilities:
	•	receive updates
	•	parse message or callback
	•	call intent layer and conversation engine
	•	format messages and keyboards
	•	send responses

Telegram code must not contain core business rules.

Target location:
	•	backend/app/integrations/telegram/

Suggested modules:
	•	bot.py
	•	client.py
	•	handlers.py
	•	callbacks.py
	•	keyboards.py
	•	formatter.py
	•	webhook.py

Important rule:
All Telegram buttons with URLs must use public URLs only.
Never use localhost or 127.0.0.1 in Telegram URL buttons.

⸻

5.2 Web admin and booking UI

Frontend is a user/admin interface layer.

Responsibilities:
	•	display data
	•	send API requests
	•	support admin workflows
	•	support public booking page

Frontend must:
	•	use /api in production
	•	be fully Russian in UI
	•	use a production build
	•	never rely on localhost in production

Target location:
	•	frontend/src/

Suggested structure:
	•	api/
	•	components/
	•	pages/
	•	features/
	•	hooks/
	•	utils/

⸻

6. Time handling architecture

Time handling must be centralized.

Rules:
	•	DB stores UTC
	•	admin input converts local -> UTC
	•	API returns UTC or formatted local values consistently
	•	UI and Telegram display expert-local time
	•	reminders calculate from booking time correctly

Target utility location:
	•	backend/app/utils/timezone.py

Expected functions:
	•	parse_local_datetime
	•	to_utc
	•	from_utc
	•	format_local_datetime

No other module should invent its own timezone math.

⸻

7. Production deployment architecture

Production deployment must be:

Browser
→ nginx
→ frontend static build

Browser
→ nginx /api
→ backend

Telegram
→ webhook
→ backend

Rules:
	•	no Vite dev server in production
	•	nginx serves built frontend
	•	nginx proxies /api
	•	nginx proxies Telegram webhook path
	•	React routes must fallback to index.html

Docker must remain the deployment basis.

⸻

8. Booking flow architecture

Canonical booking flow:
	1.	user starts interaction
	2.	consent checked
	3.	intent = booking
	4.	conversation engine determines next step
	5.	booking service provides slots
	6.	user selects slot
	7.	booking service creates booking transactionally
	8.	reminder service schedules reminders
	9.	conversation engine resets flow or marks completion
	10.	admin may confirm / cancel / reschedule later

Important:
	•	user must not loop endlessly through consent
	•	user must not get stuck in completed flow
	•	global intents must still work after booking

⸻

9. FAQ answer architecture

Canonical FAQ answer path:
	1.	detect FAQ intent
	2.	resolve matching template
	3.	if template insufficient, check KB
	4.	if KB insufficient and LLM enabled, use LLM fallback
	5.	format concise answer
	6.	suggest next buttons

FAQ must be business-safe and Russian-language.

⸻

10. Handoff architecture

Handoff mode must be explicit.

When enabled:
	•	bot stops auto reply
	•	messages still stored
	•	admin responds manually
	•	conversation stays readable in admin panel

State and DB must clearly reflect handoff mode.

⸻

11. Data ownership

Database owns:
	•	durable records
	•	UTC times
	•	bookings
	•	leads
	•	conversations
	•	settings
	•	reminders
	•	KB content
	•	templates

Conversation Engine owns:
	•	current dialog state transitions

Services own:
	•	business actions

Frontend owns:
	•	display and user interaction

Telegram integration owns:
	•	channel formatting and delivery

⸻

12. Refactoring strategy

Refactoring must follow this order:
	1.	Conversation Engine
	2.	Intent Layer
	3.	Services extraction
	4.	Timezone cleanup
	5.	CRM consistency
	6.	LLM integration
	7.	Telegram UX polish
	8.	Frontend productionization and UI polish

At every step:
	•	booking flow must stay operational
	•	docker startup must stay operational
	•	domain deployment must stay operational

⸻

13. Anti-patterns to avoid

Do not:
	•	put business logic in Telegram handlers
	•	duplicate intent detection in multiple places
	•	overwrite conversation state wholesale
	•	store local time in DB
	•	hardcode localhost in production
	•	make LLM the source of truth
	•	use Vite dev server in production
	•	mix formatting logic with DB logic
	•	patch timezone by adding/subtracting hours manually

⸻

